            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Computational Complexity

            Understanding how algorithms **scale** with input size.

            - Why some programs are fast
            - Why others slow to a crawl
            - How to reason about performance
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # What Is Computational Complexity?

            Computational complexity studies:

            - **Time complexity** ‚Üí how long an algorithm runs
            - **Space complexity** ‚Üí how much memory it uses

            Both are measured as input size grows (**n**).

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Why Complexity Matters

            Small inputs hide problems.

            Large inputs expose them.

            - Code that works for `n = 10`
            - Might fail for `n = 10‚Å∂`

            Good complexity = scalable software üöÄ

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Algorithm Complexity

            Algorithm complexity describes:

            - How execution cost grows with input size
            - Independent of hardware or programming language

            We focus on **growth rate**, not exact time.

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Big-O Notation

            Big-O describes the **upper bound** of growth.

            Common examples:
            - **O(1)** ‚Äì constant
            - **O(log n)** ‚Äì logarithmic
            - **O(n)** ‚Äì linear
            - **O(n¬≤)** ‚Äì quadratic

            ####O(n¬≤) > O(n) > O(log n)####

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Visualizing Big-O

            mermaid
            graph TD
              O1["O1 constant"] --> Olog["O log n"]
              Olog --> On["O n"]
              On --> Onlog["O n log n"]
              Onlog --> On2["O n squared"]
              On2 --> Oexp["O 2 power n"]
            /mermaid

            Lower is better!
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Time Complexity ‚è±Ô∏è

            Time complexity counts:

            - Number of operations
            - As input size **n** increases

            Example:
            - Loop over array ‚Üí **O(n)**
            - Nested loops ‚Üí **O(n¬≤)**

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Space Complexity

            Space complexity measures:

            - Extra memory used by an algorithm
            - Input memory is often ignored

            Examples:
            - Single variable ‚Üí **O(1)**
            - Extra array of size n ‚Üí **O(n)**

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Time vs Space Tradeoff ‚öñÔ∏è

            Sometimes you trade:

            - **More memory** for **faster execution**
            - Or **less memory** for **slower execution**

            Classic example:
            - Caching results (memoization)

            There is no free lunch.

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Best, Average, Worst Case

            Algorithms can behave differently:

            - **Best case**
            - **Average case**
            - **Worst case**

            Big-O usually describes the **worst case**.

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

